This info is from a CDC worker that passed this along to his family members. I'm passing it on to those I care about as well 😉.....
The new NCP coronavirus may not show sign of infection for many days, how can one know if he/she is infected. By the time they have fever and/or cough and goes to the hospital, the lungs is usually 50 % Fibrosis and it's too late!

Taiwan experts provide a simple self-check that we can do every morning:
Take a deep breath and hold your breath for more than 10 seconds. If you complete it successfully without coughing, without discomfort, stuffiness or tightness, etc.,it proves there is no fibrosis in the lungs, basically indicating no infection.

In critical times, please self-check every morning in an environment with clean air.
----
SERIOUS EXCELLENT ADVICE by Japanese Doctors treating COVID-19 cases:
Everyone should ensure your mouth & throat is moist, never DRY. Take a few sips of water every 15 mins at least. WHY? Even if the virus gets into your mouth...drinking water or other liquids will WASH them down through your esophagus into the stomach. Once there in tummy...your stomach ACID will kill all the virus. If you don't drink enough water more regularly...the virus can enter your windpipes and into the LUNGS. That's very dangerous.

Pls send and share with family, friends and everyone.

snippet.textDisplay:
So here's a question I'd like to have discussed in one of your videos:


I'm sure some people have seen the news article where Steve Wozniak suggests that he might have been 'patient Zero' (roll eyes here). However, it does make me think: about a month ago, my wife and both kids got extremely sick with what I naturally assumed was the flu. It was particularly bad, my son literally was bed ridden for seven days. My wife had it bad too. Our kids are very healthy, so anything that knocks them flat for several days makes me take notice, it's very unusual.


This makes me wonder: is it possible that the coronavirus is actually more widespread than we think, and has already passed through various regions for the past two months, and that we simply didn't pick up that it was anything but the flu? It's only when cases are severe (ie older folk with other ailments or weakened immune systems) that are being hospitalized, and that the testing has only started recently for this...


Is the media freaking out about something that might have already come & gone through our area, and we just don't realize it?


Cheers

Hi Mike, thanks for sharing your knowledge. When talking about precautions, I think at this point no one in the world would still talk to or even stand close to a person who is coughing or sneezing, so most of the cases should be caused by TALKING (which also generate droplets) closely to an asymptomatic patient or patient with mild symptoms.

So just from my personal experience I would definitely recommend getting a flu shot esp in times of a pandemic like this

snippet.textDisplay:
Very informative. There's no cure for viruses of ANY kind. There's only treatment after the fact or precautions before infections meaning take care of yourself listen to doc wash your hands , stay away from the infected , don't cough on your spouse unless your trying to get rid of them 😎. All that can be done is make the patient more comfortable while treating the symptoms because there's absolutely no cure for a virus.
I've also seen people get a flu shot only to get extremely sick, I strongly believe from the vaccines themselves. Getting a flu shot may help some but if it makes you sick and then you get this new strain on top of that your kind of sol. Double edged sword . I'm not antivaxxer just antivax the ones I think are possibly helping to grow stronger strains.
